Recently, cyber attacks on the business world have become more frequent.
Access to data from companies such as JP Morgan, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target has caused them losses of hundreds of millions, and in some cases even billions of dollars.
It doesn't take too many such attacks to damage the global economy.
The public sector is also not protected from such problems.
From 2012 to 2014, there was a significant data breach at the U.S. Office of Human Resources.
Access to trustworthiness and fingerprint data of 22 million employees was disrupted.
There are known attempts by hackers sponsored by government agencies to influence the results of elections in a number of countries with the help of stolen data.
The last two cases of disclosure of a large amount of data concern the Bundestag, the Federal Parliament of Germany, and the theft of the files of the Democratic National Committee of the United States.
The cyber threat affects our democratic processes.
The situation is even getting worse.
As computer technology evolves, data protection systems become increasingly vulnerable.
A new kind of computer technology is also of concern – computing on quantum computers, which use the microscopic properties of nature to enormously increase computing power.
It is so powerful that it will be able to crack many modern encryption systems.
Is the situation so hopeless?
Maybe it's time to pack our vital data and prepare for the imminent digital apocalypse?
I'd say, "It's not time yet."
Quantum computers are still in development, and it will take many years before they are put into practice.
More importantly, there are major breakthroughs in encryption.
For me, this is a particularly exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned about the new possibility of creating quantum effects that do not exist in nature, I was very excited.
I was intrigued by the idea of applying the fundamental laws of physics to create more secure encryption.
Today, a number of companies and laboratories around the world, including mine, are working on these technologies to put them into practice.
faithfully.
Now we are preparing to fight the quantum with the help of the quantum.
So how does it all work?
First, let's take a little digression into the world of encryption.
To do this, we will need a briefcase, some important documents that we want to send to our friend, James Bond, and a castle to keep everything safe.
Since our information is top secret, we need a special portfolio.
It has a special code lock: when it is closed, it converts all the text in documents into random numbers.
You put the documents in the briefcase, close the lock — at this very moment all the documents are converted to random numbers — and send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is on the way, you call James to tell him the code.
When he receives the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are decrypted, and voil – you just sent an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) It's a funny example, but it illustrates three important elements of coding.
Code – we call it an "encryption key.
It's like a password.
Call James to tell him the lock combination code.
It's called "key exchange" —
Ensure that you securely receive the encryption key from the right location.
And the lock that encodes and decodes the document.
This is called a "coding algorithm."
Using a key, it converts text in documents to random numbers.
A good algorithm will encode in such a way that without a key, the document is very difficult to decipher.
The importance of encryption is that if someone takes possession of a portfolio and cracks it without the help of an encryption key and an encoding algorithm, they will still not be able to read its contents.
The information will look like a set of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure way to exchange keys to pass the encryption key to the right place.
However, the rapid development of computing power threatens a number of modern key exchange methods.
Consider one of the most widely used systems today, RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was assumed that it would take 40 quadrillion years to crack the 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was cracked.
As computers got more powerful, we had to use more complex codes.
Today, we usually use 2,048 or 4,096 bits.
As you can see, code creators and hackers are engaged in an ongoing battle, trying to outwit each other.
And when quantum computers emerge in the next 10 to 15 years, they will be able to crack the complex mathematics that underpin many modern encryption systems even faster.
A quantum computer is likely to turn our current reliable fortress into a simple house of cards.
We must find a way to protect our fortress.
In recent years, there has been an increasing number of studies in the use of quantum effects to enhance crypto protection.
Some interesting discoveries have been made.
Remember the three main elements of encryption: high-quality keys, secure key exchange, and a sophisticated algorithm?
Advances in science and technology threaten two of these three elements.
First, the keys themselves.
Random numbers are the fundamental building blocks of encryption keys.
But to date, they are not entirely random.
Today, we create encryption keys from sequences of random numbers generated from software, so-called pseudo-random numbers.
In the numbers generated by a program or mathematical formula, one way or another there is a certain regularity.
The less random the numbers— in scientific terminology: the less entropy they contain — the easier it is to predict them.
Recently, several casinos have fallen victim to an inventive attack.
Combinations at the output of slot machines were recorded for some time, after which they were analyzed.
This allowed cybercriminals to redesign the pseudo-random number generator that controls the drums.
Which, in turn, made it possible to predict the rotation of the reels with high accuracy and get a big win.
Encryption keys may be subject to similar risks.
Secure encryption requires a truly random number generator.
For many years, scientists have been looking for the possibility of creating such a generator.
But most attempts today are either not random enough, not fast enough, or difficult to repeat.
But the quantum world is based on chance.
Therefore, it makes sense to take advantage of this fact.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can also create an infinite stream of random numbers at high speed,
which will prevent all these potential criminals in the casino.
A number of the best universities and companies around the world are engaged in the creation of generators of truly random numbers.
The first quantum generator created in my company was one by two meters in size and was placed on an optical table.
Later, we were able to reduce it to the size of a server box.
Today, it's the size of a PCI card connected to a standard computer.
It's the world's fastest truly random number generator.
Its performance is a billion random numbers per second.
Today, it is used to strengthen the security system by cloud providers, banks, government agencies around the world.
(Applause) But even with such a generator, the second big problem remains unsolved: the threat to secure key exchange.
Modern key exchange methods are not compatible with a quantum computer.
The quantum solution to this problem is called "quantum key distribution" or QKD, which is based on a fundamental, paradoxical characteristic of quantum mechanics.
A quantum particle changes depending on its observation.
I'll give you an example of how it works.
Let's get back to exchanging codes for the castle with James Bond.
Only this time, instead of calling James with a code message, we will use quantum effects on the laser to create code and send it to James over a regular optical fiber.
We believe that Dr. Nou will try to hack access to data exchange.
Fortunately, his attempts to catch quantum keys on the way will leave fingerprints that James and you can detect.
This will eliminate the intercepted keys.
And the remaining keys can be used for enhanced data protection.
Since such security is based on the fundamental laws of physics, a quantum computer or even any supercomputer of the future will not be able to crack it.
My team and I are working with leading universities, as well as the defense sector, to develop this promising technology into next-generation security tools.
The Internet of Things foreshadows an era when 25-30 billion devices will interact, which are projected to appear by 2020.
For our society to function properly in the world of the Internet of Things, trust in the systems that support these devices is vital.
I bet quantum technologies can provide that trust by allowing us to take full advantage of the amazing innovations that will enrich our lives.
Thank you.
