Today I would like to show you how we will do different things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be self-assembling, reproducing and repairing themselves.
So I'm going to show you what I think is the current stage of industrial development and then compare it to some natural systems.
So, at the current stage of industrial development, we have skyscrapers - 2.5 years, from 500,000 to a million parts, quite complex, new amazing technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have amazing machines that can take us into space – 5 years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we see proteins of two million species that can assemble in 10,000 nanoseconds, or a strand of DNA with three billion major pairs that we can copy in about an hour.
So, natural systems, for all their complexity, are extremely efficient, far more efficient than anything we can build, far more complex than anything we can build.
They are much more energy efficient.
They are almost never wrong.
And they can rebuild themselves over the course of a long life.
So, there's something very interesting about natural systems.
And if we can bring that into our man-made environment, our way of creating things will have tremendous potential.
And I think the key is self-in-collection.
So, if we want to use self-concassion in our physical environment, I think there are four key factors to consider.
First, we need to decipher the complexity of what we want to build – our buildings and cars.
And you need to decompose them into a simple sequence - the basic DNA of the construction processes.
