At its core, it has the most fundamental building block of computing, the logical element of a digital integrated circuit directly in each part.
It's an "AND-NOT" element.
You have one tetrahedron, an element that will do all the calculations, and two tetrahedra for input.
One for user input is how you lay bricks.
Other for information from the previous brick laid.
And then it outputs information in three-dimensional space.
So, this means that the user can start starting the movement of bricks in the right direction.
His calculations are based on what was done earlier and what you told him to do.
And now it begins to move in three-dimensional space - up or down.
On the left side, [1,1] input is equal to 0 at the output, moving down.
On the right side, [0.0] input is 1 at the output, which means upward movement.
