It is believed that only sighted people can be behind the wheel of a car.
Until recently, it was believed that for a blind person, safe and independent driving is an impossible task.
Hello, I'm Denis Hong, and we give the blind freedom and independence by developing cars for the visually impaired.
Before I talk about this car for the blind, I'll briefly talk about another project I've been working on called the DARPA Urban Challenge.
The project was to create a self-driving robot car.
The driver presses "start", and without his participation the car reaches its destination.
In 2007, our team won half a million dollars, taking third place in this competition.
Around the same time, the National Federation of the Blind, or NFS, set a research committee the task of developing a car that could be independently and safely driven by a blind person.
We decided to try our hand because we thought, "Hey, what's the big part?
We already have an autonomous car.
Put a blind man in it and it's over, right?"
(Laughter) But we were deeply mistaken.
The NSF wanted to get not just a car that would transport the blind, but a car that a blind person could drive on his own.
So we had to reject everything and start from scratch.
So, to test this crazy idea, we developed a small prototype of a buggy car to test the feasibility of the project.
And in the summer of 2009, we invited blind people from all over the country and gave them the opportunity to test this car.
It was an amazing experience.
But the catch is that this car was designed to be driven in a strictly controlled environment, namely in a flat enclosed parking lot, where even lanes are limited by red signal cones.
Due to this success, we decided to take the next big step and develop a real car that could be driven on real roads.
So how does it work?
Well, it's a pretty complicated system, but let me clarify, maybe even simplify it.
So, it includes three components.
These are tactile perception, computation and non-visual interfaces.
Since the driver does not see anything, the system must perceive the environment and collect information for the driver.
To do this, use the original parameter meter.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration, like a person's inner ear.
This information is then transmitted to a GPS device to assess the location of the vehicle.
Two cameras are used to detect lanes on the road
and three laser rangefinders.
Lasers scan the space around the car to detect various objects: an approaching oncoming or over-over-the-top car, any obstacles encountered on or around the car.
Then all this huge amount of information is fed into the computer, and the computer performs two stages.
First of all, it is the processing of this information to obtain an idea of space: determining the lanes on the road, identifying obstacles, and then bringing this information to the driver.
The system is also smart enough to calculate the safest way to drive.
So, we can also give recommendations on how to operate the machine.
But the problem is how to convey this information and instructions to a blind person who does not have the quick and accurate reaction necessary to drive?
For this purpose, we have developed a number of interface technologies for the blind:
Three-dimensional ping sound system, vibrating vest, steering wheel with sound signals, a special prosthetic leg, and even shoes that exert pressure on the leg.
But today we will talk only about three types of these special interfaces.
The first interface is called DriveGrip.
This is a pair of gloves with motors on the joints of the fingers, instructing the driver how to steer: direction and angle of rotation.
Another device is SpeedStrip.
Initially, this is a massage chair.
It was dismantled and rearranged in it vibrating elements. Vibration is used to convey speed information to the driver, as well as to guide the use of the gas and brake pedals.
So, here you can see how the computer perceives the space around the car. And since vibration cannot be seen, red LEDs are installed on the driver to demonstrate the process.
This is sensory data, it is transmitted to devices through a computer.
DriveGrip and SpeedStrip are very efficient.
But the problem is that these are training prompting devices.
They don't actually give freedom of government, do they?
The on-board computer gives the driver commands: "left", "right", "add speed", "stop".
We call it the "annoying passenger in the back seat."
Therefore, we move away from educational prompting devices and focus our attention on informing devices.
A great example of such an interface is AirPix.
This is a kind of monitor for the blind.
A small panel with many holes through which compressed air escapes, thereby creating images.
A blind person can bring his palm to this panel and "see" lanes on the roadway and obstacles.
Also, the driver can change the frequency at which the air comes out and, possibly, the temperature of the air.
That is, it is an interface for displaying multidimensional data.
So, here you see the left and right camera of the car, and how the computer processes and sends this information to the AirPix panel.
Here we demonstrate a simulator, a blind person driving a car with AirPix.
This simulator has proven to be very useful for training blind drivers, as well as for quickly testing ideas for using different types of special interfaces.
That's how this system works in a nutshell.
After all, this is a prototype car for the blind. And he will not be released on the roadway until they are convinced of his absolute safety.
And I honestly believe that's quite likely.
Still, will society accept such a radical idea?
How much will the rules of auto insurance change?
Under what conditions will a driver's license be issued?
Aside from the technological challenges, there are so many pitfalls that need to be overcome before this becomes a reality.
Of course, the main goal of this project is to develop a car for the blind.
However, it is possible that the side technologies developed during this project will prove to be an invaluable contribution to our lives.
Our sensors work regardless of the time of day, fog and rain.
We can use these technologies together with new special interfaces to improve the safety of cars for the sighted.
Or for the blind. Find them a use in everyday household appliances, in educational institutions, in offices.
Just imagine: the teacher in the classroom writes on the board, and a blind student can see and read what is written using these special interfaces.
It's priceless.
So what I showed you today is just the beginning.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
